default&#xa0;
defaultIt is an inevitable consequence of all agricultural systems that nutrients are removed from the soil an effect that can be partly mitigated by recycling. In time the soil is unable to supply sufficient available minerals which need replenishing by application of appropriate fertilisers. Apart from nitrogenous fertilisers, which can be manufactured without the use of a finite raw material (at present they rely on oil), the current raw materials for fertilisers will eventually run out
default.
default It will be necessary to use new, currently unusable, raw materials. The roots of some crops are known to exude chemicals that have the power to solubilise unavailable iron and manganese which plants can then absorb. 
defaultIt i
defaults not difficult to imagine extend
defaultin
defaultg
default this work to 
defaultall essential plant nutrients
default.    
default&#xa0;
defaultEvery effort should be made in Westminster and in the EU to facilitate the cultivation of GM crops in the UK and in Europe.
defaultWhilst it may take some time for public perception in the UK to warm to GM crops the very fact of a change will alter perceptions in many African countries where politicians are blocking GM developments because they are taking a lead from the EU. Improvements in the disease resistance of such crops as cassava and banana could make a big difference for many in Africa and be an ample reward for changes in Europe. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe arguments made by the opponents fall into two categories. Firstly arguments that are relevant to the technology itself and those that are related to the use of GM crops in the field which are basically irrelevant.
defaultNot NaturaldefaultPossibly the most commonly used argument is that the procedure is not natural and results in “
defaultfrankenfoods
default”. If natural is meant to be what nature could manage without man’s help then GM technology is not natural. But so is mutagenesis which we do not object to. 
defaultThe claim that GM food is not safe for man, animals and the environment is repeatedly made and leads to demands for long term toxicology studies to demonstrate the absolute safety of GM derived food. There can never be absolute proof that there will never be any deleterious effects of GM crops. Such absolute proof cannot be demonstrated for any human activity.
default 
defaultThe safety of all the GM crops currently grown across the world has been assessed by local regulatory bodies. The key aspect of all assessments is to determine whether the GM crop is fundamentally the same as its non-GM counterpart. 
defaultWHO, 
defaultthe American Medical Association, the US National Academy of Sciences, the UK Royal Society and 
defaultother respected scientific organisations have 
defaultall 
defaultconcluded that 
defaultGM crop
defaults pose no greater risk than crop plants modified conventional
defaultly.
default&#xa0;
defaultGenes can of course escape by pollen transfer and may successfully enter the DNA of other plants - an aspect that is monitored. The beneficial attributes transferred to another plant might help its survival. For over 50 years it has been possible for the benefits conferred by mutagenesis assisted plant breeding to be transferred to other plants without any untoward happening. It may also be pointed out that for a few hundred years we have imported plants (over 2000 species) with their foreign genes into the UK again without deleterious effects of gene transfer.  
defaultOrganic groups look upon gene transfer from a GM crop to an organic crop as contamination in order to provide a rationale for their self-ordained regulations.
default&#xa0;
defaultSuper weeds, Insecticide and fungicide resistant pests.default              defaultThe
default first attribute of GM crops was tolerance to the herbicide 
defaultglyphosate
default which meant that this herbicide could be sprayed to kill competing weeds without damaging the crop. Long before GM technology appeared it was known that repeated use of the same herbicide was likely to lead to the weed cultivars tolerant of the herbicide surviving and propagating next year. In the same way insects that are not killed by the insect resistant GM crop will survive and multiply. 
defaultThe involvement of GM technology is incidental. The problems of super weeds etc. will be solved,
default 
defaultwhether the crop is GM or not, by the use of other herbicide and pesticides and by improvements to agricultural practices.
defaultBecause Monsanto were in the vanguard with their herbicide 
defaultglyphosate
default they attracted the attention of the GM opponents. They are no longer alone 
defaultSyngenta
default (who have donated their Golden Rice work to third world farmers) and others including Bayer, BASF, Dow, Du Pont Pioneer have joined them.
defaultGM opponents ignore the basic fact that farmers are not coerced into buying anyone’s seed; they will only buy a particular variety if they perceive it to be a benefit to them. Hybrid seed has to be bought annually from the producer. The perceived unacceptable commercial practices of Monsanto are not valid reasons for rejecting GM technology. 
defaultThere is often more than one way of solving a problem but it is not logical to disregard an approach on this basis. The ways that prove easier to use, are more beneficial or are cheaper are likely to prevail. Marker assisted plant breeding is a very valuable tool and where applicable will be used. The proposed use of Golden Rice to combat the deadly vitamin A deficiency by improving the diet is simpler and cheaper than the alternative solution of providing 6 monthly vitamin A supplements to all children less than 5 years.
